<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: COUNTYWIDE; 
</P>
<P>
'ABANDONED' ISLANDERS BUILD CORE OF FOLLOWERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RUSS CHARVONIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There weren't any stretch limos delivering 7-foot-tall players earning 
seven-figure salaries. But fans of the Santa Barbara Islanders nonetheless were 
treated to a spirited basketball game Sunday night as the local favorites were 
defeated by the Rapid City Thrillers, 127-100. 
</P>
<P>
The Islanders -- whose players average about $10,000 annually -- became an 
abandoned franchise in February after the Continental Basketball Assn. team's 
managing partner reportedly failed to pay rent at the team's former home, Santa 
Barbara City College. 
</P>
<P>
Association officials decided to move the club to Ventura College to complete 
post-season play and Ventura has since welcomed the team with open arms. 
</P>
<P>
And now that the "Cinderella" Islanders have advanced to the final round of the 
national conference playoffs, their local popularity has been even greater. 
While an estimated 600 fans travel from Santa Barbara to Ventura to view the 
games, most of those attending recent games were from Ventura County. 
</P>
<P>
"This is my first game," said Tom Flaminio of Ventura. "I'm here primarily out 
of curiosity," he said. 
</P>
<P>
The Islanders are up against the wall following Sunday's loss, which put the 
Thrillers of South Dakota ahead 3-2 in the best of seven series. Unless the 
Islanders win both remaining games Monday and Tuesday, fans may have witnessed 
their final professional basketball game in Ventura for a while. 
</P>
<P>
The CBA considered permanently relocating the Islanders to Ventura County about 
six months ago, but the absence of a local arena that could accommodate 6,000 
fans forced the league to scuttle the idea, said CBA Vice President Bob King. 
"We were very impressed with the demographics in the Ventura area," King said. 
</P>
<P>
The CBA, which took over ownership of the Islanders after the previous 
management defaulted on payments, is talking to about 10 groups who may want to 
buy the team and keep them in Santa Barbara, King said. The franchise fee is 
about $600,000. 
</P>
<P>
"This is great basketball," said Steve Rifkind, a Solvang doctor who claims to 
be the Islanders' first season ticket-holder. "Half the players came from the 
NBA, and the other half is headed for the NBA." 
</P>
<P>
Victoria Kearny, who accompanied Rifkind to the game, recalled that he often 
would "drive to the top of San Marcos pass so that he could receive the radio 
broadcasts of Islander away games." 
</P>
<P>
If the Santa Barbara Islanders prove victorious in the final games against the 
Thrillers, they will advance to the league championship playoffs against either 
LaCrosse, Wis., or Albany, N.Y. RUSS CHARVONIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Islanders fans cheer on their team, above, LAWRENCE K. HO / Los Angeles 
Times; Photo, as the Santa Barbara players face off against opponents from 
Rapid City at Ventura College. The tenacious Islanders have advanced to the 
final round of the national conference playoffs. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
