<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: SCIENCE/TECHNOLOGY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Dean Takahashi, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Delta II Launch: McDonnell Douglas Space Systems Co. in Huntington Beach plans 
to launch a Delta II rocket for the government of Indonesia at 6:28 p.m. 
Thursday from Cape Canaveral, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
The rocket's mission is to deliver a Palapa B-2R communications satellite to 
geostationary orbit 22,300 miles above the Equator. 
</P>
<P>
The satellite will join two Palapa satellites already in orbit and 
electronically link the people of Indonesia with their island neighbors through 
high-speed data relays and telephone and television signals. Each Delta II 
rocket launch generates about $50 million in revenue for McDonnell Douglas, 
said Anne McCauley, a company spokeswoman. The company plans 12 launches in 
1990. 
</P>
