<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: OF HURT'S BABY, 'BATMAN II' AND ELEPHANT SAVIOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE TRAUMA of William Hurt's "palimony" trial last year and the possibility of 
a second go-round in court hasn't hurt the actor's marriage to Heidi Henderson. 
Bill and Heidi, who live in the East, are expecting their second child. This 
time they hope for a girl to go with their Sam, age 7 months. But neither 
parent believes in finding out a baby's sex in advance, so they just have to 
wait and see what happens in August. And so do we. 
</P>
<P>
AS IF THERE isn't enough turbulence in Great Britain these days, now the movie 
industry of Blighty is up in arms over news that the "Batman" sequel will be 
shot in Mexico instead of in England. The fantastic, $5-million "Gotham City" 
set has been kept intact at Pinewood Studios for more than a year, at a cost of 
$100,000-a-month storage. And that, of course, is in anticipation of Michael 
Keaton's "doing it again." But perhaps Warner Bros. doesn't feel obligated to 
honor commitments made by their ex-Batmoguls, Jon Peters and Peter Guber, who 
now do their stuff for Columbia Pictures. 
</P>
<P>
MARLENE SANDERS was the first woman to cover the Vietnam War close up, so she 
is no stranger to the vicissitudes of foreign travel. And it's a good thing, 
too, because her recent trip to Nepal, for the Discovery Channel's "Profiles in 
Progress" series, had Marlene traveling both by Land Rover and by elephant. 
</P>
<P>
The elephants were just wonderful, Marlene says, but the Rover got stuck in the 
middle of a raging river, and the plucky correspondent had to be rescued by 
canoe. The Land Rover was then brought out by elephant. 
</P>
<P>
ON MONDAY Sotheby's in New York will be the site for the Manhattan Center for 
Living's gala benefit "Fantasy Auction." (The MCL helps people with 
life-threatening diseases.) Mike Nichols and Steve Sondheim of the Broadway 
theater are co-chairing this event, which offers about 40 fantasies donated by 
stars of entertainment, music, fashion and sport. 
</P>
<P>
You'll be able to bid for tickets to see the great Maggie Smith in "Lettuce and 
Lovage," then meet and sip Champagne with her backstage, and go on to dine with 
"L&amp;L" playwright Peter Shaffer at Orso's. (I have dined myself with this 
writing giant who created "Amadeus," and whoever wins him will be in for a 
treat.) 
</P>
<P>
The sports-minded might land the right to go with Susan Sarandon, her "Bull 
Durham" cutie, Tim Robbins, and TV sports commentator Tim McCarver to lunch at 
the Regency, take in a New York Mets game, and meet the team. (We are not 
talking cheesy little fantasies here!) 
</P>
<P>
Sotheby's expects bidding to go through the roof for one particular fantasy 
Breakfast at Tiffany's with Audrey Hepburn. The highest bidder, plus a guest, 
will enjoy a private fast-breaking with the star in the executive offices of 
the jewelry emporium. So two lucky people get to discover whether food ever 
passes those elegant Hepburn lips. 
</P>
</TEXT>
